Per me Reges regnant, By me Kings raigne, is the generall ground of the Charter, both of good and evill Princes, and Nobles, and all the Judges of the earth, (Prov. 8. 15, 16.) He it is that raiſeth unto David a righteous branch, a King who ſhall raigne and proſper, and execute judgement and juſtice Jer. 33. 5, 6. Hoſ. 13. 11. upon the earth, in whoſe dayes the people ſhall be ſafe; And he it is that gives an evill King in his anger, and takes a good King away in his wrath; Qui regnare facit hominem hypocritam propter peccata populi, (Job. 34. 30.) vulg. So that whether they be good or evill, we muſt be ſubject, ſithence there is no power but of God; 
   〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
, leſt we will be found fighters againſt God, whoſe power none is able Act. 5. 39. to reſiſt, whether it bee for protecting or for puniſhing; [Wherefore we muſt needs be ſubject.]
